-- Google, Fendi, EBay, FIFA, Pork Board, Ringtones: Intellectual Property
-- Victoria Slind-Flor
-- 2010-06-23T11:01:01Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-06-23/google-fendi-ebay-fifa-pork-board-ringtones-intellectual-property.html

          
          
             Google Inc. , operator of the world’s
largest Internet search engine, was sued by  Frontier
Communications Corp.  and accused of infringing a new patent for
enhanced telephone services.  
 Google is violating patent rights with products such as the
Google Voice system, Frontier, based in Stamford, Connecticut,
contended yesterday in a complaint in federal court in Delaware.  
 “Google’s deliberate infringement of the patent has
greatly and irreparably damaged Frontier,” the plaintiff’s
lawyers said in court papers seeking unspecified damages and an
injunction to stop the use of the technology.  
 Google, based in Mountain View, California, agreed last
month to buy  Global IP Solutions Holding AB , a maker of voice
and videoconferencing software, for about $68 million to help
expand Internet video and audio capabilities.  
 “We believe these claims are entirely without merit, and
we’ll defend against them vigorously,” Andrew Pederson, a
spokesman for Google, said by e-mail.  
 Frontier is represented by  Mary B. Graham  of Wilmington,
Delaware’s  Morris, Nichols, Arsht & Tunnell LLP .  
 The case is Frontier Communications Corp. v. Google Inc.,
10-cv-545, U.S. District Court, District of Delaware
(Wilmington).  
 Nathan Myhrvold Gets Patent for ‘Displaceable’ Medical Device  
 Nathan Myhrvold , the former chief technology officer at
 Microsoft Corp. , is a named inventor on a patent for a device
that can be used to support a portion of the human body.  
 Patent 7,740,015, one of  4,163 U.S. patents  issued
yesterday, covers a “medical displaceable contouring
mechanism.”  
 The device can be used to support a portion of the body,
such as an injured leg, while limiting pressure on the patient,
according to the patent. It contains multiple displaceable
contouring units that can move up or down and through a variety
of angles in order to support and stabilize the body portion.  
 The mechanism could be used in hospitals and nursing homes,
to stabilize broken bones, or to limit the formation of bed
sores.  
 The patent is assigned to The Invention Science Fund 1 LLC,
of Bellevue, Washington. Myhrvold formed Bellevue-based
 Intellectual Ventures  in 2000 after leaving Microsoft. The
company has a number of separate entities such as The Invention
Science Fund to which patents are assigned.  
 Of the 13 inventors named on the patent in addition to
Myhrvold, many are listed on the Intellectual Ventures website
as senior inventors. The application for the patent was filed in
October 2006.  
